We first look at the “Purchase” transactions that were not paid in cash/bank but were recorded as “Unpaid” with the “Account Payable” payment method. In our file the starting (“initial”) balances come only from the “Initial” entries (cash deposit, bank deposit, fixed assets) – none of which add anything to accounts payable – so the beginning accounts payable balance is 0.00.

Then we scan the “Purchase” transactions (by their ids and table rows) and note those that are “Unpaid” (payment/receipt_status = Unpaid) and – importantly – that use “Account Payable” as the payment_method. In our list these are:

1. Transaction with id Purchase20231231009 – amount = 60,000.0  
2. Transaction with id Purchase20231231013 – amount = 250,000.0  
3. Transaction with id Purchase20231231018 – amount = 60,000.0  

All other purchase transactions were “Paid”. Adding these three amounts gives:
  60,000 + 250,000 + 60,000 = 370,000.0

Thus, at the end of the period the total amount still owed (i.e. “Accounts Payable End Value”) is 370,000.00.

So our answer is:

{
  "Accounts Payable Initial Value": "0.00",
  "Accounts Payable End Value": "370000.00"
}
